<$fill $name="body">

!! Two modes

|!Mode |!Widget |!Description |!Tools |
|Chat |`<$llm-chat>` |Multi-turn conversation with message history |Yes (configurable) |
|Action |`<$llm-action>` |One-shot invocation: context → LLM → output |Optional |

!! Data flow — Chat mode

```
User types message
    ↓
Chat widget reads context template (first message only)
    ↓
Context rendered (text or markup mode)
    ↓
Context attachments resolved (text tiddlers + file_ref markers for binaries)
    ↓
Just before API call: file_ref markers resolved → base64 content blocks
    ↓
Messages + tools sent to LLM via adapter
    ↓
Response parsed → tool calls? → execute → send results → loop
    ↓
Final text response → save to chat tiddler → UI refresh
```

!! Data flow — Action mode

```
Button triggers <$llm-action>
    ↓
Context resolver: find template (precedence chain)
    ↓
Render template with currentTiddler
    ↓
Single API call (or tool loop if tools enabled)
    ↓
Write response to output target (field / new tiddler / display / filter)
```

!! Components

|!Module |!Type |!Description |
|`orchestrator.js` |library |Tool-use loop, conversation management, HTTP requests, `file_ref` resolution |
|`adapter-claude.js` |library |Claude API: request building, response parsing, tool results, multimodal blocks |
|`adapter-openai.js` |library |OpenAI API: same interface, different format, multimodal blocks |
|`adapter-azure.js` |library |Azure OpenAI API: same as OpenAI with deployment/version config |
|`tool-executor.js` |library |Tool dispatch, restricted wiki proxy creation, wikitext execution |
|`context-resolver.js` |library |Template precedence, rendering (text/markup), context attachment resolution |
|`file-resolver.js` |library |File detection (`_canonical_uri`), classification (image/document), base64 fetching |
|`chat-widget.js` |widget |`<$llm-chat>` — chat UI, message management, debug panel |
|`action-widget.js` |widget |`<$llm-action>` — one-shot invocation, output writing |
|`startup.js` |startup |Module verification on browser load |
|`ui/chat-panel.tid` |PageTemplate |Global chat panel, toggled from page toolbar |
|`ui/pair-edit.tid` |ViewToolbar |Per-tiddler pair-edit toggle button |
|`ui/pair-edit-panel.tid` |ViewTemplate |Embedded chat panel below tiddler body for pair editing |
|`ui/drag-panel.js` |startup |Makes the chat panel draggable by its header |
|`context-templates/pair-edit.tid` |context-template |Sends raw wikitext source for collaborative editing |

!! Data flow — Pair editing

```
User clicks pair-edit toolbar button
    ↓
$reveal panel opens below tiddler body (ViewTemplate)
    ↓
<$llm-chat> initialised with currentTiddler + pair-edit context template
    ↓
First message sends tiddler's raw wikitext as context
    ↓
LLM reads/edits via get_tiddler + set_field tools → immediate execution + audit log
    ↓
User sees changes live (filesystem-watcher or syncer refresh)
```

!! Chat panel

The global chat panel is rendered via `$:/tags/PageTemplate` (not a popup). It is toggled by the page toolbar button and made draggable by `drag-panel.js`, which switches from bottom/right to top/left positioning on mousedown and constrains the panel to the viewport.

!! Context template precedence

# ''Tiddler field'' — `llm-context-template` on the source tiddler
# ''Prompt template'' — `context-template` field on the prompt template tiddler
# ''Widget attribute'' — `contextTemplate` on `<$llm-chat>` or `<$llm-action>`
# ''Global default'' — `$:/config/rimir/llm-connect/default-context-template`
# ''Built-in'' — render source tiddler's text as plain text

!! Output modes

* ''text'' — wikify template output to plain text (for content-level help)
* ''markup'' — preserve raw wikitext/HTML (for wiki-programming help)

!! Tiddler protection — allow/deny modes + restricted wiki proxy

Protection supports two modes, configurable in Settings and per-chat:

* ''Allow mode (whitelist)'' — default. Only filter-matched tiddlers are accessible; everything else is blocked. Empty filter = no access.
* ''Deny mode (blacklist)'' — filter-matched tiddlers are hidden; everything else is accessible. Empty filter = full access.

Each mode has its own base filter (`$:/config/rimir/llm-connect/allow-filter` and `$:/config/rimir/llm-connect/protection-filter`). Filters are combined in multiple layers: base config + widget attributes + per-chat fields + base protection + excluded plugins + hard protection + help page access (see security docs for full order).

All tool wikitext executes against a ''restricted wiki proxy'' rather than the real `$tw.wiki`. The proxy is created via `Object.create($tw.wiki)` and overrides core access methods so blocked tiddlers are completely invisible:

|!Method |!Behaviour for blocked titles |
|`getTiddler(title)` |returns `undefined` |
|`getTiddlerText(title, default)` |returns `default` |
|`tiddlerExists(title)` |returns `false` |
|`isShadowTiddler(title)` |returns `false` |
|`each(callback)` |skips blocked titles |
|`forEachTiddler(options, callback)` |skips blocked titles |
|`eachShadow(callback)` |skips blocked titles |
|`eachTiddlerPlusShadows(callback)` |skips blocked titles |
|`eachShadowPlusTiddlers(callback)` |skips blocked titles |
|`addTiddler(tiddler)` |silently blocked |
|`deleteTiddler(title)` |silently blocked |

The proxy has its own `filterCache` so compiled filters bind `self` to the proxy rather than the real `$tw.wiki`. This ensures all filter operations (including `[all[shadows+tiddlers]]`) respect the proxy's overridden iteration methods.

The protection filter is evaluated once per tool call. Tools that take an explicit `title` parameter also get an early "Access denied" error before wikitext execution (defense-in-depth).

''Auto-expanding filter'': when a tool successfully executes with a `title` or `basetitle` input, the orchestrator adds the created title to the in-flight protection filter. For `basetitle` mode, the actual resolved title is extracted from the result string (`Done — created tiddler '...'`). After the conversation turn completes, the widget persists the updated filter to the chat tiddler.

The `create_tiddler` tool supports two modes: `title` (exact, fails if exists) and `basetitle` (auto-numbered: tries base, then base + ` 1`, ` 2`, ... up to ` 20`). The LLM always receives the actual title created in the result. The restricted wiki proxy is temporarily expanded during creation to allow writing only non-existing titles — existing tiddlers remain protected from overwrite.

!! Multimodal context — file attachments

Binary files (PDFs, images) stored via `_canonical_uri` can be attached to conversations. The flow uses a two-phase approach to avoid storing large base64 data in the message history:

```
Context filter evaluated (📎 input + llm-context field on source tiddler)
    ↓
file-resolver classifies each title → text tiddler or file tiddler
    ↓
Text tiddlers: rendered content included inline
File tiddlers: file_ref marker stored in message (URI + mediaType only)
    ↓
Just before API call: orchestrator.resolveFileRefs()
    ↓
XHR fetches each file → arraybuffer → base64
    ↓
adapter.buildFileBlock() converts to provider format:
  Claude: { type: "image"|"document", source: { type: "base64", ... } }
  OpenAI/Azure: { type: "image_url"|"file", ... }
```

Supported formats: JPEG, PNG, GIF, WEBP (image), PDF, DOCX, XLSX (document). Max file size configurable via `$:/config/rimir/llm-connect/max-file-size` (default 20 MB).

!! Document extraction — text instead of base64

When extraction is enabled (default), PDF/DOCX/XLSX files are converted to markdown text before sending to the LLM. This replaces the base64-encoded binary with plain text — dramatically reducing token usage.

```
file_ref block for .pdf/.docx/.xlsx detected in resolveFileRefs()
    ↓
Check cache: does "<title>.extracted" tiddler exist?
    ↓ yes → use cached text
    ↓ no  → call /api/extract?uri=<canonical_uri> (runner plugin)
              ↓
           extract-route.js resolves URI → filesystem path
              ↓
           Runs pdftotext (PDF), pandoc (DOCX), or python3 xlsx-to-md.py (XLSX)
              ↓
           Returns markdown text → cached as "<title>.extracted" tiddler
    ↓
Extracted text injected as { type: "text" } block instead of base64
    ↓
Falls back to base64 if extraction fails (runner unavailable, unsupported format)
```

The extraction route resolves `_canonical_uri` paths to filesystem paths — supports both `files/` (TiddlyWiki built-in) and scattered-binaries profiles. Cache tiddlers persist across restarts via the filesystem adapter.

!! Model tier routing

Tools can be assigned a cost tier via the `tool-model-tier` field: `cheap`, `default`, or `expensive`. When tier routing is enabled, the orchestrator switches the model after each tool round based on the highest tier among the called tools.

```
Tool round completes → determine max tier among called tools
    ↓
cheap → switch to cheap tier model (e.g. haiku)
default → use chat's selected model (no switch)
expensive → switch to expensive tier model (e.g. sonnet)
    ↓
Next API call uses the switched model
    ↓
After next tool round, re-evaluate and switch again if needed
```

Tier routing is same-provider only — cross-provider switching is blocked because message formats differ between adapters. The layers icon (⚡) in the chat header shows the current config on hover and toggles tier routing on click.

!! Accessible tiddlers panel

The chat widget includes an accessible tiddlers panel (👁️ icon) that visualises the effective protection filter. It evaluates the combined filter (base + widget attributes + per-chat), runs it against all tiddlers, and renders the resulting accessible titles as clickable navigation links.

Drag-and-drop modifies the per-chat filter to grant access: `[[title]]` is appended in allow mode, `-[[title]]` in deny mode. The panel, protection input, and debug preview all refresh on change.

!! Chat pin/save/restore

Chat tiddlers use `$:/temp/` paths — the syncer excludes these from sync, so they exist only in browser memory and are lost on reload. The pin feature creates a persistent copy at `$:/saved-chats/rimir/llm-connect/<context-slug>` (one slot per widget context).

When pinned, `syncPinnedSave()` is called from: `saveMessages()` (messages), `refresh()` (tool changes via wikitext), `saveProtectionInput()`, mode switch handler, context filter handler, and `handleAccessDrop()`. This ensures all state changes are captured.

On restore, `restoreChat()` copies all fields back to the chat tiddler and restores widget-instance flags (`contextInjected`, `attachmentsInjected`, `systemPromptOverride`) to prevent duplicate context injection.

!! Source tiddler auto-access

`resolveProtectionForChat()` automatically adds the `sourceTiddler` (from the `tiddler` attribute) to the effective filter — `[[title]]` in allow mode, `-[[title]]` in deny mode. This ensures pair-edit always has tool access to the tiddler being edited.

!! Debug panel system

The 🐛 button opens a dropdown menu listing inspection panels. The active panel renders inside `inputArea` above the button row (toolbar always stays at bottom). Architecture:

* ''Panel registry'' — built at render time by `buildDebugPanelRegistry()`. Merges built-in JS panels (preview, sent, response, accessible tiddlers, logging) with wikitext panels discovered via tag `$:/tags/rimir/llm-connect/debug-panel`.
* ''JS panels'' — render into a content div via `panel.render(el)`. Preview/sent/response use `<pre>` elements updated by `refreshDebugPanel()`.
* ''Wikitext panels'' — parsed via `$tw.wiki.parseTiddler()`, rendered via `makeWidget()` with `chatTiddler` variable. Widget ref stored for `refresh(changedTiddlers)`.
* ''Toggle panels'' — no debug area; execute a callback (e.g. tristate tool-call display).
* ''Logging'' — `this.log(category, message)` appends timestamped entries to `this.debugLog[]`. Orchestrator receives `onLog` callback for tool/tier/request events.

</$fill>
</$transclude>
