!! Overview

llm connect executes LLM-requested operations against the wiki store. This section describes the security boundaries, what is protected, and what is not.

!! API key storage

API keys are stored in wiki config tiddlers (`$:/config/rimir/llm-connect/providers/<name>/api-key`). They are visible to anyone with file access to the wiki. This is suitable for personal wikis or server wikis with authentication. API keys are never sent to the LLM — only to the respective provider API endpoint.

!! Protection modes — allow & deny

The protection system supports two modes, selectable in Settings and per-chat via the shield icon:

* ''Allow mode (whitelist)'' — default. Only tiddlers matched by the allow filter are accessible. Everything else is invisible. With an empty filter the LLM has no tiddler access at all.
* ''Deny mode (blacklist)'' — tiddlers matched by the deny filter are hidden. Everything else is accessible.

Switching modes via the shield icon automatically negates the per-chat filter — each filter run's `-` prefix is toggled, preserving the user's intent. For example, `[[Foo]] [tag[bar]]` becomes `-[[Foo]] -[tag[bar]]` when switching from allow to deny.

Each mode has its own base filter configured in Settings:

* Allow base filter: `$:/config/rimir/llm-connect/allow-filter` — defines which tiddlers are accessible in whitelist mode
* Deny base filter: `$:/config/rimir/llm-connect/protection-filter` — defines which tiddlers are blocked in blacklist mode

Two additional cross-mode filters enforce protection regardless of the active mode:

* ''Base protection filter'': `$:/config/rimir/llm-connect/base-protection-filter` (default: `[tag[sensitive]]`) — part of the base filter chain. Subtracted in allow mode, added in deny mode.
* ''Hard protection filter'': `$:/config/rimir/llm-connect/hard-protection-filter` (default: `[tag[sensitive]]`) — applied ''after'' all user input (per-chat filters, drag-drop, widget attributes). Cannot be overridden. Shown with a lock icon below the per-chat filter input.

This ensures that `tag[sensitive]` tiddlers are never accessible, even if they appear in a pair-edit whitelist (e.g. because they're linked from the edited tiddler).

To hide additional tiddlers, extend the filters in Settings or use the excluded-plugins checkbox list to block entire plugin namespaces.

!! Restricted wiki proxy

All tool wikitext executes against a restricted wiki proxy rather than the real `$tw.wiki`. The proxy is created via `Object.create($tw.wiki)` and overrides core access methods so blocked tiddlers are invisible:

* `getTiddler`, `getTiddlerText`, `tiddlerExists`, `isShadowTiddler` — return undefined/false/default
* `each`, `forEachTiddler` — skip blocked titles
* `addTiddler`, `deleteTiddler` — silently blocked

Filter operators (`is[tiddler]`, `get`, `has`, etc.) go through the overridden accessors automatically since the proxy sits on the prototype chain. No post-filtering of results is needed.

!! Protection filter layers

Protection filters are combined in this order:

# ''Mode-specific base filter'' — configured in Settings for the active mode (allow or deny). Always active.
# ''Widget attributes'' — `denyFilter` and `allowFilter` on `<$llm-chat>` / `<$llm-action>`. Useful for recipe-based panels that need specific access rules.
# ''Base protection filter'' — always enforced regardless of mode. Subtracted in allow, added in deny.
# ''Per-chat filter'' — additional filter set via the shield icon. Stored on the chat tiddler.
# ''Excluded plugins'' — plugins ticked in settings are blocked.
# ''Hard protection filter'' — absolute final gate. Applied after everything else. Cannot be overridden.
# ''Help page access'' — when the llm-help plugin is installed, all help pages, the functions tiddler, and help temp tiddlers are always accessible. Added after hard protection (hard protection still wins for `[tag[sensitive]]` help pages).

All layers are concatenated into a single filter expression. Per-chat mode can be overridden via the mode dropdown in the shield panel.

!! Defense-in-depth

Tools that take an explicit `title` parameter (e.g. `get_tiddler`, `set_field`, `delete_tiddler`) check the title against the active filter ''before'' wikitext execution. In allow mode, the title must be in the filter results; in deny mode, it must not be. This provides a clear "Access denied" error message rather than a silent "not found". The restricted wiki proxy provides the second layer — even if a tool bypasses the title check (e.g. via wikitext transclusion), the proxy blocks access.

''Special handling for `create_tiddler`'': new tiddlers (that don't exist yet) are allowed through the title check — the tiddler can't be in any filter if it doesn't exist. The restricted wiki proxy is temporarily expanded to allow writing only non-existing titles during creation (existing tiddlers remain protected from overwrite). If a tiddler with that title already exists, the tool returns an error directing the LLM to use `set_field` instead. After successful creation, the orchestrator automatically adds the new title to the active protection filter so subsequent tool calls in the same conversation can access it. The updated filter is persisted to the chat tiddler.

!! What is NOT protected

* ''The LLM conversation itself'' — messages are stored in the chat tiddler as plain JSON. Anyone with wiki access can read them.
* ''API traffic'' — requests go directly from the browser to the provider API over HTTPS. No data passes through a third-party proxy, but the provider can see all content.
* ''Tool execution'' — action-mode tools (`set_field`, `create_tiddler`, `delete_tiddler`) execute immediately. There is no confirmation step. An audit log is written to `$:/temp/rimir/llm-connect/write-log` but it is a temp tiddler (not persisted across reloads).
* ''System prompt and context'' — the LLM sees the system prompt, context template output, and all context attachments. It can be instructed via prompt injection in tiddler content.
* ''Unprotected tiddlers'' — in deny mode, any tiddler not matched by the deny filter is fully accessible. In allow mode, only explicitly allowed tiddlers are accessible.

!! Multimodal file attachments

Files attached via the context filter are fetched from the server via XHR, base64-encoded in the browser, and sent inline in the API request. The max file size is enforced client-side (`$:/config/rimir/llm-connect/max-file-size`, default 20 MB). Files are not cached — they are re-fetched on each send.

!! Accessible tiddlers panel

The chat widget includes an accessible tiddlers panel (👁️ icon) that shows a live, scrollable list of all tiddler titles the LLM can currently access based on the active protection mode and filters.

* In ''allow mode'', the list shows tiddlers matched by the combined allow filter. An empty filter means an empty list (no access).
* In ''deny mode'', the list shows all tiddlers ''not'' matched by the combined deny filter.

The panel supports drag-and-drop: dropping a tiddler onto the panel grants LLM access to it. In allow mode this appends `[[title]]` to the per-chat allow filter. In deny mode this appends `-[[title]]` to the per-chat deny filter (exempting it from the blacklist). The per-chat filter input (shield icon) updates automatically to reflect the change.

The list includes both real tiddlers and shadow tiddlers. It refreshes automatically when the protection mode, base filter, per-chat filter, or excluded plugins config changes.

!! Source tiddler auto-access

When the `tiddler` attribute is set on the chat widget (e.g. pair-edit mode), the source tiddler is automatically included in the effective protection filter. In allow mode `[[title]]` is appended; in deny mode `-[[title]]` is appended. This ensures the LLM can always read and modify the tiddler it is pair-editing, without the user needing to manually add it to the allow list.

!! Recommendations

* Start with allow mode (default) — grant access only to the tiddlers the LLM needs
* When switching to deny mode, tag sensitive tiddlers with `sensitive` or extend the deny filter
* Use widget-level `allowFilter` / `denyFilter` attributes for recipe panels with specific access needs
* Avoid storing secrets (passwords, tokens) in accessible tiddlers — the LLM can read them via tools
* Review the audit log after LLM interactions that modify tiddlers
* Consider using read-only tool groups when the LLM only needs to search and read

</$fill>
</$transclude>
