<$fill $name="body">

!! Object.create($tw.wiki)

The restricted wiki proxy is created via `Object.create($tw.wiki)`, which produces an object that inherits all methods from the real wiki but allows overriding individual methods (like `getTiddler`, `filterTiddlers`, `addTiddler`) to enforce tiddler protection. This is a lightweight, zero-copy approach that avoids duplicating the entire wiki store.

!! $tw.wiki.filterTiddlers

Used extensively by the tool executor to run user-defined filters (e.g., `search_tiddlers` tool). The restricted wiki proxy overrides this to strip protected titles from filter results, ensuring the LLM never sees protected tiddler titles even through indirect filter queries.

!! $tw.wiki.renderText

The context resolver uses `renderText(type, "text/vnd.tiddlywiki", text, {variables})` to wikify context templates. This runs the full TiddlyWiki rendering pipeline including transclusion, macro expansion, and widget execution — producing plain text or wikitext output depending on the output mode.

!! module-type: widget

`chat-widget.js` and `action-widget.js` are registered as custom widgets. `<$llm-chat>` extends TW's `Widget` class and manages its own DOM lifecycle (message list, input area, debug panel). `<$llm-action>` is an action widget that executes during `invokeActions()` — it runs the LLM call and writes the result.

!! $:/tags/PageTemplate

The global chat panel (`ui/chat-panel.tid`) is tagged `$:/tags/PageTemplate`, making it render as a page-level element (alongside the story river, sidebar, etc.). Visibility is controlled via a `$reveal` widget watching a state tiddler toggled by the page toolbar button.

!! $:/tags/ViewTemplate

The pair-edit panel (`ui/pair-edit-panel.tid`) is tagged `$:/tags/ViewTemplate`, injecting it into every tiddler's view. A `$reveal` widget gates rendering based on a per-tiddler state tiddler, so the panel only appears when the user clicks the pair-edit toolbar button.

!! XMLHttpRequest

The orchestrator uses raw `XMLHttpRequest` (not `fetch`) for LLM API calls to maintain compatibility with older TiddlyWiki environments. The request is built by the provider adapter and sent as JSON with appropriate headers (Authorization, Content-Type).

</$fill>
</$transclude>
